'''Limassol District''' ({{IPAc-en|<U+02C8>|l|<U+026A>|m|<U+0259>|s|<U+0252>|l}}) or '''Lemesos''' ({{lang-el|<U+039B><U+03B5><U+03BC><U+03B5><U+03C3><U+03CC><U+03C2>}} {{IPA-el|leme<U+02C8>sos|}}; {{lang-tr|Limasol}} or {{lang|tr|''Leymosun''}}; {{lang-arm|<U+053C><U+056B><U+0574><U+0561><U+057D><U+0578><U+056C>}}) is one of the six [[districts of Cyprus]]. {{As of|2011}}, it had a population of 235,330, 77% of which was urban.<ref>{{cite web|title=Population <U+2013> Place of Residence, 2011|url=http://www.cystat.gov.cy/mof/cystat/statistics.nsf/All/7F6BB26ED9D00A00C2257AD90055542A/$file/POP_CEN_11-POP_PLACE_RESID-EN-170414.xls?OpenElement|website=Statistical Service of Cyprus (CYSTAT)|date=17 April 2014}}</ref> Its main city is [[Limassol]]. Part of the [[British Overseas Territory]] of [[Akrotiri and Dhekelia]] forms an enclave on the [[Akrotiri Peninsula (Cyprus)|Akrotiri Peninsula]], under the sovereignty of the [[United Kingdom]].

==History==
The buried ancient city of [[Amathus]] is {{convert|11|km}} from Limassol. Archaeological excavations have unearthed ruins of the Byzantine period and a tomb of the 7th century BC.{{Sfn|Wei<U+00DF>|Sabo|Peitz-Hlebec|Schwarz|2001|p=28}} The ancient [[Kolossi Castle]], which is located {{convert|9|km}} to the west of Limassol, reflects the fall of [[Acre]] and history of the [[Templars]] and their confiscated property allotted to the Limassol District for cultivation of wine and sugarcane.{{Sfn|Wei<U+00DF>|Sabo|Peitz-Hlebec|Schwarz|2001|p=26, 28}}

==Geography==
[[File:Kouris_Dam_-_overflow_day_8_April_2012.jpg|right|thumb|The [[Kouris Dam]].]]
Limassol District forms much of the southwestern-central part of Cyprus. The [[Kouris River]] rises in the southern slopes of [[Troodos mountains]], which lie in the northern part of the district towards the centre of Cyprus, and flows to the sea near the ancient city of [[Kourion]]. This river has been dammed by the [[Kouris Dam]], which has caused the near drying up of the river in its lower reaches.{{Sfn|Jasink|Bombardieri|2010|p=1}} Limassol, to the northeast of the Akrotiri peninsula lies on [[Akrotiri Bay]], while [[Pissouri]], to the northwest of the peninsula, lies on [[Episkopi Bay]].<ref>{{Google maps | url =https://www.google.com/maps/place/34%C2%B047%2700.0%22N+32%C2%B055%2700.0%22E/@34.6722618,32.9724119,43970m/data=!3m1!1e3!4m2!3m1!1s0x0:0x0?hl=en  | accessdate =19 April 2015}}</ref> Episkopi Bay is a nesting ground for [[green sea turtle|green]] and [[loggerhead turtle]]s, both of which are on the [[International Union for Conservation of Nature|IUCN]] list of endangered species.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://wcd.coe.int/com.instranet.InstraServlet?command=com.instranet.CmdBlobGet&InstranetImage=1921561&SecMode=1&DocId=1776560&Usage=2|title=Sea turtle mortality in the British Sovereign Base 
Areas (SBAs) of Episkopi and Akrotiri (Cyprus) |publisher=31
st Standing Committee Meeting of the Contracting Parties to the Convention on the 
Conservation of European Wildlife and Natural Habitat|accessdate=19 April 2015}}</ref> Amathous Beach and the Dassoudi Beach are also situated in the district.
{{-}}
