==Landmarks==
[[File:Cyprus - Limassol castle 5.JPG|thumb|Limassol Castle]]
Limassol, as the regional capital and a major centre for European tourism, contains many of the administrative and cultural buildings, and a large number of hotels along the seafront. Limassol District Court is located on Lord Byron Avenue near the Limassol city centre. It consists of a court complex with multiple buildings.<ref name=supremecourt.gov.cy>{{cite web|title=Limassol District Court|url=http://www.supremecourt.gov.cy/Judicial/SC.nsf/All/EC613F991D288949C22572C0003BCD06?OpenDocument|publisher=Supreme Court of Cyprus|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref> The city is known for its wineries, and revelry and nightlife.{{Sfn|Wei<U+00DF>|Sabo|Peitz-Hlebec|Schwarz|2001|p=25}} 

The Limassol District Archaeological Museum, located in Limassol, has historical artefacts from the towns of Kourion and [[Amathus]].{{Sfn|Wei<U+00DF>|Sabo|Peitz-Hlebec|Schwarz|2001|p=26}} The collections cover several periods, including Preneolithic (Akroteri culture), Early Neolithic (Shillourokambos culture), Neolithic I, Neolithic II (Sotira culture), Chalcolithic, Erimi Culture, Early Bronze Age, <U+039C>iddle Bronze Age, Late Bronze Age, Cypro-Geometric period, Cypro-Archaic period, Cypro-Classical period, Hellenistic period, Roman period, and Late Roman/Early Christian/Early Byzantine period.<ref name=limassolmunicipal.com>{{cite web|title=The Limassol District Archaeological Museum|url=http://www.limassolmunicipal.com.cy/museum/buton1-eng.html|publisher=Limassol Municipal Government|accessdate=18 April 2015}}</ref>

===World Heritage site===
Painted churches in the [[Troodos Mountains|Troodos range]], inscribed as a World heritage Site in 1985, lie in the district of Limassol and also in the [[Nicosia District]]. This site has churches and monasteries of the erstwhile [[Byzantine empire]]. The paintings are elaborately embellished large wall paintings which belong to both pre and post Byzantine period. These paintings and frescoes feature on both the exterior and interior walls of the churches.{{Sfn|Spilling|Spilling|2009|p=136}}<ref name=Heritage>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cyprusembassy.net/home/index.php?module=page&pid=12|title= Cultural Heritage of Cyprus|accessdate=17 April 2015|publisher=Embassy of the Republic of Cyprus in Washington D.C.}}</ref>

